I used to work at Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and part of my job was to do lar=
ge trades with corporate clients. These trades had positive expected value =
to Goldman (otherwise why do them?). Sometimes Goldman did=C2=A0100% of the=
 trade with the client; other times we had to split it with other banks. It=
 was desirable to have a piece of the trade, and we generally tried to get =
100% of it, because, again, positive expected value.=C2=A0A thing that neve=
r happened in my time at Goldman was this:Lloyd Blankfein, Goldman=E2=80=99=
s chief executive officer at the time: Hey Matt.[1]Me:=C2=A0=E2=80=99Sup=C2=
=A0Lloyd.Lloyd: I hear you=E2=80=99re negotiating a lucrative trade with XY=
Z Corp.Me (proudly): Sure am, Lloyd, let me tell you about it.[2]Lloyd: I w=
ant a piece of it.Me:=C2=A0Well great news, actually we=E2=80=99re=C2=A0get=
ting 100% of it, I have successfully persuaded the client to do the whole t=
rade with us on a relationship basis. JPMorgan has been pushing to get in b=
ut =E2=80=94=C2=A0Lloyd: No I don=E2=80=99t mean I want a piece of it for G=
oldman, I want a piece of it for me.Me: What?=C2=A0Lloyd: It=E2=80=99s lucr=
ative, I need some money, I=E2=80=99m your boss, give me 10% of the trade.M=
e: What?I am not saying that versions of this never happened elsewhere at G=
oldman. There are situations where senior Goldman people get economics dire=
ctly from the firm=E2=80=99s deals rather than just as part of their year-e=
nd compensation; Goldman=E2=80=99s partners get investment opportunities in=
 funds run by the firm that invest in merchant-banking deals. There are obv=
ious potential conflicts of interest there, though also potential alignment=
 of interest when the partners invest alongside the clients;=C2=A0presumabl=
y Goldman=E2=80=99s board of directors thinks about these things and approv=
es them carefully. But it would be unusual for a senior executive=C2=A0to m=
osey up to a line banker and say =E2=80=9Chey I am a little strapped for ca=
sh this month,=C2=A0cut me into your deal in my personal account.=E2=80=9DA=
nyway  this made me laugh nervously:[Current Goldman] Chief Executive Offic=
er David Solomon and his deputies, who=E2=80=99ve contended with mounting p=
ressure to reward trainees this year, have been searching for ways to juice=
 their own eight-digit pay packages.Among the ideas floated: partaking in a=
 cut of the richest rewards thrown off by Goldman=E2=80=99s own SPACs, the =
blank-check companies that are all the rage on Wall Street. =E2=80=A6These =
ventures =E2=80=94 special purpose acquisition companies =E2=80=94 raise =
=C2=A0money from the public to go hunting for acquisition targets. The big =
pull for SPAC managers is what=E2=80=99s known in the business as the =E2=
=80=9Cpromote=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 a compensation structure that typically le=
ts founders acquire 20% of the venture=E2=80=99s shares at a steep discount=
. Stakes purchased for thousands of dollars can quickly soar into the milli=
ons.Goldman operates an in-house SPAC business even as it advises outsiders=
 on their own. The firm already has rolled out two SPACs and disclosed plan=
s to create several more.At Goldman, much of the promote is expected to ben=
efit the bank, but portions have been set aside for executives directly inv=
olved in the ventures, people familiar with the matter said.Solomon has pus=
hed to expand the allocation of founder shares to a small group in the bank=
=E2=80=99s upper management. That=E2=80=99s irritated members of the SPAC t=
eam =E2=80=94 essentially pitting them against the CEO for a share of the s=
poils. =E2=80=A6Internal teams have been scrambling to figure out how to st=
ructure and disclose the SPAC investment for the [named executive officers]=
 while avoiding the appearance of boosting pay. The proposal may yet fail t=
o go through, two of the people said.Honestly giving the SPAC executives a =
piece of the promote is a little weird =E2=80=94=C2=A0they=E2=80=99re Goldm=
an employees! this is their job! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I get it; technically t=
hey are also executives of a public company (the SPAC) and so should probab=
ly own some of it directly. Giving the promote to the executives is =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0just =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know =E2=80=A6=C2=A0why not pa=
y them more? Instead of giving them pieces of some of the bank=E2=80=99s de=
als, why not just give them one big bonus at the end of the year that repre=
sents how well the bank performed on=C2=A0all=C2=A0of its deals? Isn=E2=80=
=99t that how this normally goes?That passage is from Sridhar Natarajan=E2=
=80=99s Bloomberg story about how Goldman=E2=80=99s senior management would=
 like to get paid more, in part because everyone else seems to be getting r=
eally really rich while Goldman executives are stuck making mid-eight-figur=
e paychecks, but also because James Gorman made fun of them:When Goldman wa=
s finalizing Solomon=E2=80=99s package in early 2020, it wanted to reward h=
im for the stock=E2=80=99s best annual performance since 2013. But Morgan S=
tanley CEO James Gorman, whose shares were also on a tear, pulled out a sur=
prise by trimming his own pay about 7% to $27 million. Goldman, caught off =
guard, delayed disclosing its compensation decision that January.=C2=A0Gorm=
an was aware of that dynamic and privately needled Goldman executives about=
 it.I need much more reporting about how that went? Otherwise I=E2=80=99m g=
oing to make it up:Interior Goldman office. David Solomon=E2=80=99s phone r=
ings.Solomon: Yes?His assistant: It=E2=80=99s James Gorman for you.Solomon:=
 That must be serious. Put him through.Gorman: Hello David. I=E2=80=99m afr=
aid there=E2=80=99s a terrible financial crisis brewing and I thought all t=
he major bank CEOs should get on the same page. Of course=C2=A0you were my =
first call.Solomon: Uh oh, what=E2=80=99s the problem?Gorman: YOU AIN=E2=80=
=99T GETTING PAID AHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHA.Honestly they should own that. =
The board should write the compensation discussion in the next proxy statem=
ent like =E2=80=9Cwe needed to give David Solomon another $20 million becau=
se otherwise James Gorman would make fun of him and we can=E2=80=99t have t=
hat.=E2=80=9D What do you think investment bank compensation is actually ab=
out?Anyway let me suggest two possible answers=C2=A0to my question above, a=
bout why bank executives would want to be paid in slices of deals rather th=
an in one overall bonus. One is: People pay attention to a bank CEO=E2=80=
=99s end-of-year bonus, and if it is too high they will yell at the bank; p=
eople pay less attention to the promote share on the bank=E2=80=99s individ=
ual SPAC deals and so you can hide compensation there. This seems to be par=
t of the consideration; here=E2=80=99s Natarajan:As memories of 2008=E2=80=
=99s taxpayer-funded bailouts give way to rising public awareness of income=
 inequality, many bank boards remain wary of paying executives too lavishly=
.That often leaves directors playing a guessing game, seeking to raise CEO =
pay in line with what rivals do =E2=80=94 while taking care not to overshoo=
t and draw attention.Another possible answer is: =E2=80=9CA basket of optio=
ns is worth more than an option on a basket.=E2=80=9D If you are the CEO of=
 Goldman Sachs, each year there will be some good news and some bad news. Y=
our equity underwriting business will have a banner year but you=E2=80=99ll=
 pay a bunch of money to  settle a scandal in Malaysia, that sort of thing.=
 You will go to the board for your bonus, and they will say =E2=80=9Cwell y=
ou had some wins and some losses, overall they balance out to you being wor=
th $27.5 million. But actually the Malaysia stuff is really high-profile an=
d embarrassing so we=E2=80=99re going to publicly dock you $10 million for =
that, so, $17.5 million.=E2=80=9D That is, they add up all the pluses and a=
ll the minuses, net them out, and give a bit of extra weight to the most em=
barrassing minuses.But what if instead of going to your board for a bonus e=
very year, you just got a bit of upside on every transaction? Some of the t=
ransactions would be good, and you=E2=80=99d make money on your slice of th=
e upside. Some of the transactions would be bad, and your slice of the upsi=
de would be worth zero,=C2=A0but not less than zero. Effectively you=E2=80=
=99d get your comp by adding up the pluses and ignoring the minuses. This i=
s better!=C2=A0Getting a share of the SPAC promote is not literally that =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0there is some downside risk =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it has that b=
asic profile of extremely asymmetric upside. If you can get your compensati=
on at a bank by picking the bank=E2=80=99s most favorable positions =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the places where the bank gets the most asymmetric upside =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0and grabbing a share of them, that is strictly better than having =
the board pay you based on the bank=E2=80=99s overall performance. That=E2=
=80=99s how you get really rich! If you=E2=80=99re a hedge-fund manager, yo=
ur job is not to lumber along running a diversified global business; it=E2=
=80=99s to pick the best spots with the most asymmetric upside and concentr=
ate your money there. If you=E2=80=99re a bank CEO, it is hard to replicate=
 that. But you can try.
