   =20
      Trump SPAC
   =20
 =20
In October, Donald Trump  announced a plan to have retail investors give hi=
m $293 million in exchange for about 18% to 25% ownership of an=C2=A0imagin=
ary new media company that he=E2=80=99s pretending to start.[3] So far this=
 seems to be going great. The company =E2=80=94=C2=A0Trump Media & Technolo=
gy Group =E2=80=94 remains pretty imaginary; it has provided no updates on =
its financials, operations, plans, etc., and it =E2=80=9Cappears to have mi=
ssed the November deadline it set to release an invitation-only beta versio=
n of =E2=80=98Truth Social,=E2=80=99 its purported alternative to Twitter.=
=E2=80=9D (That quote is from a hilarious CNBC article that also says =E2=
=80=9CThe media relations officer for the company, Roma Daravi, has not twe=
eted about TMTG and Truth Social since October=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CIt is =
also unclear who is actually building the network.=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0Meanwhile=
 the deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0between TMTG and a special purpose acquisition com=
pany called Digital World Acquisition Group =E2=80=94=C2=A0has not yet clos=
ed, or even filed a proxy statement containing TMTG=E2=80=99s financial sta=
tements, so Trump hasn=E2=80=99t actually gotten his $293 million. But the =
signs are good. The way the SPAC works is that Trump gets $10.20 for each s=
hare of DWAC that converts into a share of TMTG; DWAC shares closed yesterd=
ay at $44.35. Retail investors and Trump political allies will pay $44 for =
the right to give Trump $10. He=E2=80=99s gonna get his money.Still, it is =
going=C2=A0so=C2=A0well that he is trying to get more money. Specifically h=
e is going to hedge funds and asking them to pay a billion dollars for abou=
t 25% ownership of TMTG:Former President Donald Trump's new social media ve=
nture is seeking to raise up to $1 billion by selling shares to hedge funds=
 and family offices at several times the valuation it commanded in a deal w=
ith a blank-check acquisition firm in October, two people familiar with the=
 matter said. =E2=80=A6Trump Media is now seeking to raise up to an additio=
nal $1 billion at a valuation of close to $3 billion, to reflect Digital Wo=
rld's share rally after Trump supporters and day traders snapped up the sto=
ck, the sources said.Basically retail investors think that TMTG is worth $4=
4=C2=A0a share, but for SPAC-structure reasons Trump can only collect $10.2=
0 per share from them. So he=E2=80=99s going to hedge funds and asking for =
like $36 per share from them.=C2=A0Will that work? Man, I don=E2=80=99t kno=
w, but I laughed a lot at this:Digital World shares were valued at $10 each=
 in the deal with Trump Media. Trump Media is now looking to secure a so-ca=
lled private investment in public equity (PIPE) that would value Digital Wo=
rld shares closer to their recent price, the sources said.The sources added=
 that Digital World shares may be valued based on a 20% discount of their 1=
0-day, volume-weighted average price.That sounds so =E2=80=A6=C2=A0real? Li=
ke, official and scientific and efficient-markets-y? =E2=80=9CThe best indi=
cation of the value of TMTG is the trading price of its common stock,=E2=80=
=9D is the implicit theory here, =E2=80=9Cso we will calculate that trading=
 price over some averaging period and then sell you the stock at a healthy =
20% discount to that price.=E2=80=9D This is how lots of deals are done!It =
is obviously insane here? That $44, or whatever, price of DWAC is pretty mu=
ch a random number built on sentiment; it was $60.82 a month ago and $9.94 =
a month before that. At no point has anyone buying or selling DWAC stock se=
en any business plan or financial projections for DWAC; at no point has any=
one done a trade based on a detailed financial model grounded in the compan=
y=E2=80=99s actual business. Nor has anyone used the product, found it good=
, and gone out to buy the stock. It=E2=80=99s all entirely imaginary, but a=
lso worth $44.35 a share.Is this relevant to the hedge funds and family off=
ices approached about the PIPE? I don=E2=80=99t know? On the one hand, you =
might think that sophisticated big-money investors would care about underwr=
iting the actual value of the company, that they=E2=80=99d only buy stock a=
t $36 per share or whatever if they thought that reflected the fundamental =
value of the underlying cash flows.On the other hand, you might =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0not =E2=80=A6=C2=A0think that? A reasonable pitch to a hedge fund mig=
ht be =E2=80=9Clook, buy this stock for $36 per share, because some sucker =
will buy it from you for $44 because they love Donald Trump, and the proof =
of that is that it=E2=80=99s actually trading at $44 per share.=E2=80=9D  T=
hat logic is=C2=A0risky, now, because (1) the SPAC deal won=E2=80=99t close=
 (and the PIPE investors won=E2=80=99t get their shares) for a while,[4] (2=
) between now and then TMTG will have to disclose some information about it=
s business, and (3) if that information is bad or nonexistent then the stoc=
k will presumably trade down. (Also, even after the SPAC deal closes, the P=
IPE investors may not be able to sell their shares for a while, due to regi=
stration requirements or lock-up agreements.) Agreeing to buy at $36 now be=
cause the stock is at $44, without any fundamental reason to think that the=
 stock should be at $44, seems a little crazy. But the stock=C2=A0is=C2=A0a=
t $44. That is an important data point.Also the stock was up this morning b=
ecause of the rumored PIPE deal. Part of the appeal of investing in the PIP=
E is that doing the PIPE will validate TMTG as a real company and so push u=
p the public stock price.=C2=A0The sophisticated hedge-fund PIPE investors =
will validate the retail investors, which will push the stock up, which wil=
l make the hedge funds richer.=C2=A0The retail investors are betting on the=
 PIPE investors who are betting on the retail investors. Nobody needs a bus=
iness plan; they=E2=80=99ve got each other.=C2=A0Everything I write about i=
s so stupid. I=E2=80=99m sorry. When Trump=E2=80=99s SPAC deal was first an=
nounced, I wrote: =E2=80=9CIt does feel a little bit like all of recent fin=
ancial history has been leading up to this moment.=E2=80=9D Everything I wr=
ite about these days has this essential profile: Meme stocks and crypto and=
 NFTs are all bets on=C2=A0attention rather than on underlying cash flows. =
But if you have to be in the business of betting on attention, betting on D=
onald Trump does seem relatively safe.
