<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Executive comp</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I used to work at Goldman Sachs Group =
Inc. and part of my job was to do large trades with corporate clients. Thes=
e trades had positive expected value to Goldman (otherwise why do them?). S=
ometimes Goldman did=C2=A0100% of the trade with the client; other times we=
 had to split it with other banks. It was desirable to have a piece of the =
trade, and we generally tried to get 100% of it, because, again, positive e=
xpected value.=C2=A0A thing that never happened in my time at Goldman was t=
his:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Lloyd Blankfein, G=
oldman=E2=80=99s chief executive officer at the time: </strong>Hey Matt.[1]=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Me:</strong>=C2=A0=E2=80=99Sup=C2=
=A0Lloyd.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Lloyd:</strong> I hear yo=
u=E2=80=99re negotiating a lucrative trade with XYZ Corp.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;"><strong>Me (<em>proudly</em>):</strong> Sure am, Lloyd, let =
me tell you about it.[2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Lloyd:</st=
rong> I want a piece of it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Me:</st=
rong>=C2=A0Well great news, actually we=E2=80=99re=C2=A0getting 100% of it,=
 I have successfully persuaded the client to do the whole trade with us on =
a relationship basis. JPMorgan has been pushing to get in but =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Lloyd:</strong> No I don=E2=80=
=99t mean I want a piece of it for Goldman, I want a piece of it for me.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Me:</strong> What?=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Lloyd:</strong> It=E2=80=99s lucrative, I need=
 some money, I=E2=80=99m your boss, give me 10% of the trade.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Me:</strong> What?</p></blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">I am not saying that versions of this never happened else=
where at Goldman. There are situations where senior Goldman people get econ=
omics directly from the firm=E2=80=99s deals rather than just as part of th=
eir year-end compensation; Goldman=E2=80=99s partners get investment opport=
unities in funds run by the firm that invest in merchant-banking deals. The=
re are obvious potential conflicts of interest there, though also potential=
 <em>alignment </em>of interest when the partners invest alongside the clie=
nts;=C2=A0presumably Goldman=E2=80=99s board of directors thinks about thes=
e things and approves them carefully. But it would be unusual for a senior =
executive=C2=A0to mosey up to a line banker and say =E2=80=9Chey I am a lit=
tle strapped for cash this month,=C2=A0cut me into your deal in my personal=
 account.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25905928.281656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMDIvaG93LW11Y2gtZG9lcy1nb2xkbW=
FuLXNhY2hzLWNlby1tYWtlLWRhdmlkLXNvbG9tb24tdHJpZXMtdG8tYm9vc3QtcGF5P2NtcGlkP=
UJCRDEyMDIyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0=
dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTIwMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cBe86fd199" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> this made me laugh nervously</a>:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Current Goldman] Chief Executive Officer Da=
vid Solomon and his deputies, who=E2=80=99ve contended with mounting pressu=
re to reward trainees this year, have been searching for ways to juice thei=
r own eight-digit pay packages.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Among the i=
deas floated: partaking in a cut of the richest rewards thrown off by Goldm=
an=E2=80=99s own SPACs, the blank-check companies that are all the rage on =
Wall Street. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These ventures =E2=
=80=94 special purpose acquisition companies =E2=80=94 raise =C2=A0money fr=
om the public to go hunting for acquisition targets. The big pull for SPAC =
managers is what=E2=80=99s known in the business as the =E2=80=9Cpromote=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=94 a compensation structure that typically lets founders acqu=
ire 20% of the venture=E2=80=99s shares at a steep discount. Stakes purchas=
ed for thousands of dollars can quickly soar into the millions.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman operates an in-house SPAC business even as it =
advises outsiders on their own. The firm already has rolled out two SPACs a=
nd disclosed plans to create several more.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
At Goldman, much of the promote is expected to benefit the bank, but portio=
ns have been set aside for executives directly involved in the ventures, pe=
ople familiar with the matter said.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Solomon=
 has pushed to expand the allocation of founder shares to a small group in =
the bank=E2=80=99s upper management. That=E2=80=99s irritated members of th=
e SPAC team =E2=80=94 essentially pitting them against the CEO for a share =
of the spoils. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Internal teams hav=
e been scrambling to figure out how to structure and disclose the SPAC inve=
stment for the [named executive officers] while avoiding the appearance of =
boosting pay. The proposal may yet fail to go through, two of the people sa=
id.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Honestly giving the SPAC e=
xecutives a piece of the promote is a little weird =E2=80=94=C2=A0they=E2=
=80=99re Goldman employees! this is their job! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I get it;=
 technically they are also executives of a public company (the SPAC) and so=
 should probably own some of it directly. Giving the promote to the executi=
ves is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0just =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0why not pay them more? Instead of giving them pieces of some of the bank=
=E2=80=99s deals, why not just give them one big bonus at the end of the ye=
ar that represents how well the bank performed on=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>of=
 its deals? Isn=E2=80=99t that how this normally goes?</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">That passage is from Sridhar Natarajan=E2=80=99s Bloomberg stor=
y about how Goldman=E2=80=99s senior management would like to get paid more=
, in part because everyone else seems to be getting really really rich whil=
e Goldman executives are stuck making mid-eight-figure paychecks, but also =
because James Gorman made fun of them:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">When Goldman was finalizing Solomon=E2=80=99s package in early 2020=
, it wanted to reward him for the stock=E2=80=99s best annual performance s=
ince 2013. But Morgan Stanley CEO James Gorman, whose shares were also on a=
 tear, pulled out a surprise by trimming his own pay about 7% to $27 millio=
n. Goldman, caught off guard, delayed disclosing its compensation decision =
that January.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gorman was aware of tha=
t dynamic and privately needled Goldman executives about it.</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I need much more reporting about how that we=
nt? Otherwise I=E2=80=99m going to make it up:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;"><em>Interior Goldman office. David Solomon=E2=80=99s phone =
rings.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Solomon: </strong>Yes?<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>His assistant:</strong> It=E2=80=99=
s James Gorman for you.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Solomon:</s=
trong> That must be serious. Put him through.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;"><strong>Gorman:</strong> Hello David. I=E2=80=99m afraid there=E2=80=99s=
 a terrible financial crisis brewing and I thought all the major bank CEOs =
should get on the same page. Of course=C2=A0you were my first call.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Solomon:</strong> Uh oh, what=E2=80=99s th=
e problem?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Gorman:</strong> YOU AIN=
=E2=80=99T GETTING PAID AHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHA.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Honestly they should own that. The board should write =
the compensation discussion in the next proxy statement like =E2=80=9Cwe ne=
eded to give David Solomon another $20 million because otherwise James Gorm=
an would make fun of him and we can=E2=80=99t have that.=E2=80=9D What do y=
ou think investment bank compensation is actually about?</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Anyway let me suggest two possible answers=C2=A0to my questio=
n above, about why bank executives would want to be paid in slices of deals=
 rather than in one overall bonus. One is: People pay attention to a bank C=
EO=E2=80=99s end-of-year bonus, and if it is too high they will yell at the=
 bank; people pay less attention to the promote share on the bank=E2=80=99s=
 individual SPAC deals and so you can hide compensation there. This seems t=
o be part of the consideration; here=E2=80=99s Natarajan:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As memories of 2008=E2=80=99s taxpayer-funded ba=
ilouts give way to rising public awareness of income inequality, many bank =
boards remain wary of paying executives too lavishly.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">That often leaves directors playing a guessing game, seeking to =
raise CEO pay in line with what rivals do =E2=80=94 while taking care not t=
o overshoot and draw attention.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Another possible answer is: =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/25905928.281656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMTAvbWNraW5zZXktcGFydG5lci1zLWluc2lkZXItdHJhZ=
GluZy1zdHJhdGVneS13YXMtYmFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMDIyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRp=
dW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTIwMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGF=
pZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB367ab40e" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">A basket of =
options is worth more than an option on a basket</a>.=E2=80=9D If you are t=
he CEO of Goldman Sachs, each year there will be some good news and some ba=
d news. Your equity underwriting business will have a banner year but you=
=E2=80=99ll pay a bunch of money to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/25905928.281656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDctMjQvZ29sZG1hbi1kb2VzLWEtbWFsYXlzaWEtZGVhbD9jbXBp=
ZD1CQkQxMjAyMjFfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2x=
ldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMTEyMDImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB36fe4e1e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> settle a scandal in Malaysia</a>, that sort =
of thing. You will go to the board for your bonus, and they will say =E2=80=
=9Cwell you had some wins and some losses, overall they balance out to you =
being worth $27.5 million. But actually the Malaysia stuff is really high-p=
rofile and embarrassing so we=E2=80=99re going to publicly dock you $10 mil=
lion for that, so, $17.5 million.=E2=80=9D That is, they add up all the plu=
ses and all the minuses, net them out, and give a bit of extra weight to th=
e most embarrassing minuses.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But what if in=
stead of going to your board for a bonus every year, you just got a bit of =
upside on every transaction? Some of the transactions would be good, and yo=
u=E2=80=99d make money on your slice of the upside. Some of the transaction=
s would be bad, and your slice of the upside would be worth zero,=C2=A0<em>=
but not less than zero</em>. Effectively you=E2=80=99d get your comp by add=
ing up the pluses and ignoring the minuses. This is better!=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Getting a share of the SPAC promote is not literally=
 that =E2=80=94=C2=A0there is some downside risk =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it has =
that basic profile of extremely asymmetric upside. If you can get your comp=
ensation at a bank by picking the bank=E2=80=99s most favorable positions =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the places where the bank gets the most asymmetric upside =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and grabbing a share of them, that is strictly better than h=
aving the board pay you based on the bank=E2=80=99s overall performance. Th=
at=E2=80=99s how you get really rich! If you=E2=80=99re a hedge-fund manage=
r, your job is not to lumber along running a diversified global business; i=
t=E2=80=99s to pick the best spots with the most asymmetric upside and conc=
entrate your money there. If you=E2=80=99re a bank CEO, it is hard to repli=
cate that. But you can try.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content=
